// BUG-650 (2026-05-02): compound (struct.field) handle merge across CFG join.
//
// Pre-fix, `ir_merge_states` used bare-only handle lookups
// (`ir_find_handle`), so a compound handle freed in one branch did NOT
// widen to MAYBE_FREED at the join point. Second loop's bare-keyed
// dedup also re-added pred's compound entries, producing duplicate rows
// where a stale ALIVE entry could hide the FREED state from later
// use-site lookups (non-deterministic — sometimes ALIVE was returned
// first, allowing silent UAF through the IR analyzer).
//
// On main today, the AST `zercheck.c` legacy analyzer ALSO sees this
// case via different logic and reports the error. After Phase G deletes
// `zercheck.c`, the IR analyzer becomes the sole exit-code driver, and
// without this fix the compound case becomes a silent UAF gap.
//
// Fix: both lookups in `ir_merge_states` now use
// `ir_find_compound_handle` keyed on (local_id, path, path_len). Add
// uses `ir_alloc_handle_slot` directly (bypassing bare-only
// `ir_add_handle`).
//
// EXPECTED: zercheck use-after-free / maybe-freed error on the use of
// `b.h` after the conditional free.

struct Task { u32 id; }
struct Box { Handle(Task) h; }
Pool(Task, 4) pool;

u32 main(u32 cond) {
    Box b;
    Handle(Task) tmp = pool.alloc() orelse return;
    b.h = tmp;                  // compound (b, ".h") tracked ALIVE
    if (cond > 0) {
        pool.free(b.h);         // compound = FREED in this branch
        // Falls through to merge — no early return.
    }
    // After merge: compound state must be MAYBE_FREED.
    return pool.get(b.h).id;
}
